@martinjandijkstra3205:

It's a good experiment, though. While there hasn't been a lot of news from it lately, the Ion Power Group posted some videos a few years ago where they used long wires with specific shapes and of specific materials elevated to ~130 feet suspended between poles, and during stormy weather they managed to achieve a peak output of ~30 mA of continuous current at ~41,200 V, for a total continuous power of 1.236 kW.

That's certainly a lot better, but even that isn't ultimately that impressive considering the work involved; you'd need even better harvesters suspended even higher. However, when you start calculating how much energy is stored in the Earth-ionosphere capacitor, you realize that it's actually not that much compared to the energy of the sunlight continuously striking Earth, it's actually quite little in comparison, so I don't think it's really a promising source of energy for the future, but maybe.
